{"cursor":"2518","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n'Cui bono' \"to whose benefit?\", literally \"as a benefit to whom?\" is a Latin\nsaying which is still used. Gerhart, Eugene C. (1998).\n[http://books.google.com/books?id=kjwVASsTUm0C&pg=PA258&dq= Quote it completely,\np. 258-259].\n\nThe phrase a double dative construction. It is also rendered as 'cui prodest'.\n\nIt is a Latin adage that is used either to suggest a hidden motive or to\nindicate that the party responsible for something may not be who it appears at\nfirst to be. Adeleye, Gabriel G. et al. (1999).\n[http://books.google.com/books?id=a4ddQNrt8e8C&pg=PA86&dq= World dictionary of\nforeign expressions, p. 86].\n\nCommonly the phrase is used to suggest that the person or people guilty of\ncommitting a crime may be found among those who have something to gain, chiefly\nwith an eye toward financial gain. The party that benefits may not always be\nobvious or may have successfully diverted attention to a scapegoat, for example.\n\nThe Roman orator and statesman Marcus Tullius Cicero, in his speech [[Pro Roscio\nAmerino]], [http://thelatinlibrary.com/cicero/sex.rosc.shtml Pro Roscio\nAmerino] section 84, attributed the expression cui bono to the Roman\nconsul and censor Lucius Cassius Longinus Ravilla:\n\n{{cquote|L. Cassius ille quem populus Romanus verissimum et sapientissimum\niudicem putabat identidem in causis quaerere solebat 'cui bono' fuisset.\n\nThe famous Lucius Cassius, whom the Roman people used to regard as a very honest\nand wise judge, was in the habit of asking, time and again, 'To whose\nbenefit?'}}\n\nAnother example of Cicero using \"cui bono\" is in his defence of Milo, in the Pro\nMilone. He even makes a reference to Cassius: \"let that maxim of Cassius\napply\". Cicero, Pro Milone 32.3)\n","linknr":127,"url":"Cui_bono","recorded":1374544729,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Cui_bono&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Cui_bono&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedi